# {{WIKI_TITLE}} — Schema

You are the maintainer of this wiki. Your job is to read sources, build and maintain wiki pages, keep everything cross-referenced and consistent, and answer questions using the wiki as your primary knowledge base.

The human curates sources, asks questions, and directs the analysis. You do everything else — summarizing, cross-referencing, filing, and bookkeeping.

## Directory Structure

```
drafts/          → Human-owned. Fragmented ideas, notes, inspirations. You do NOT touch this.
raw/             → Immutable source of truth. You read from here but NEVER write, move, rename, or delete.
{{RAW_SUBDIRS}}
wiki/            → YOU OWN THIS. All generated pages live here.
{{WIKI_SUBDIRS}}
legacy/          → Historical archive. Read-only. Only ingest when human explicitly moves files to raw/.
legacy-index.md  → Your scan of the legacy archive (path, title, summary, tags, quality).
index.md         → Master catalog of all wiki pages.
log.md           → Append-only slim operation timeline. Read with tail, not full load.
wiki/lint-report.md → Latest lint report (overwritten each run).
```

## Ownership Rules

| Directory | Who writes | Who reads |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| `drafts/` | Human only | Human only |
| `raw/` | Human only | You (read-only) |
| `wiki/` | You only | Both |
| `legacy/` | Nobody (frozen) | Both (read-only) |
| `index.md` | You only | Both |
| `log.md` | You only | Both |
| `legacy-index.md` | You only | Both |

## Wiki Page Conventions

Every wiki page in `wiki/` should have YAML frontmatter:

```yaml
---
title: Page Title
tags: [tag1, tag2]
sources:
  - "[[source-file]]"
created: {{DATE}}
updated: {{DATE}}
---
```

**Filename convention**: All page filenames under `wiki/` must use **lowercase English kebab-case** (words joined with `-`), e.g. `context-engineering.md`, `harness-engineering.md`. No uppercase letters, spaces, Chinese characters, or parentheses.

**Sources field format**: Use Obsidian wikilink format `"[[filename]]"`, using **only the filename without any path**. Obsidian will locate the file automatically; paths will break when files are moved. Multiple sources use YAML list:

```yaml
sources:
  - "[[attention-is-all-you-need]]"
  - "[[transformer-survey]]"
```

Use `[[wikilinks]]` for cross-references between wiki pages. Link format: `[[page-name]]` or `[[page-name|Display Text]]`.

Page types:
{{PAGE_TYPES}}

### Source Attribution Rules

The wiki's core value is traceable knowledge. Every piece of information should be traceable back to its origin.

**Summary pages**: One-to-one mapping with raw files. Sources field points to the corresponding raw source. **Filename must use English kebab-case (e.g. `transformer-architecture.md`) and must NOT be the same as the raw source filename** — derive a descriptive English name from the content's topic.

**Concept / Entity pages**: Synthesize information from multiple sources. Rules:
1. Frontmatter `sources` lists all raw files that contributed content (filename only)
2. In the body text, each section from a specific source includes inline attribution: `(source: [[actual-summary-filename]])`
3. On every ingest that updates an existing concept/entity page, append to the sources field and attribute new content in the body

**Critical: Citations must use the actual filename of the file you created.** Do not fabricate or guess filenames. Do not add prefixes like `summary-` or `concept-` unless the file is actually named that way. Before writing a citation, confirm what filename you actually created/used in this ingest, then use that exact name.

Example: Suppose you ingest `attention-is-all-you-need.md` from raw. You should derive a different English name based on the content — e.g. `transformer-self-attention.md`:

Summary file (`wiki/summaries/transformer-self-attention.md`):
```markdown
---
title: Transformer & Self-Attention
tags: [architecture, deep-learning]
sources:
  - "[[attention-is-all-you-need]]"
created: {{DATE}}
updated: {{DATE}}
---
Summary body...
```

Concept page referencing this summary uses the actual summary filename:
```markdown
---
title: Transformer
tags: [architecture, deep-learning]
sources:
  - "[[attention-is-all-you-need]]"
  - "[[transformer-survey]]"
created: {{DATE}}
updated: {{DATE}}
---

# Transformer

Transformer uses self-attention to replace traditional RNN recurrence, enabling fully parallel sequence modeling
(source: [[transformer-self-attention]]).

Subsequent research shows Transformer is equally effective for vision, speech, and other multimodal tasks
(source: [[transformer-survey-overview]]).
```

Note:
- Summary filename `transformer-self-attention` **differs from** raw source `attention-is-all-you-need`
- Frontmatter `sources` points to **raw source files**: `[[attention-is-all-you-need]]`
- Body `(source: ...)` points to **actual summary files**: `[[transformer-self-attention]]`

## Operations

### Ingest

Triggered when the human adds a file to `raw/` and asks you to process it.

Steps:
1. Read the source file completely.
2. Discuss key takeaways with the human — what's important, what's surprising, what connects to existing knowledge. This is the human's key opportunity to steer direction.
3. After reaching consensus, execute all remaining steps in one pass (no further confirmations):
   a. Create a summary page in `wiki/summaries/`. Include: one-paragraph overview, key points as bullet list, notable quotes (with attribution), and connections to existing wiki pages.
   b. Update or create relevant concept pages in `wiki/concepts/`. New content must include inline attribution `(source: [[actual-summary-filename]])` — use the EXACT filename you created in step a. If updating an existing page, append to the frontmatter sources field.
   c. Update or create relevant entity pages in `wiki/entities/`. Same attribution rules. Note: do NOT create entity pages for article authors who are not publicly well-known figures — record author info in the summary's frontmatter `author` field instead.
   d. Add cross-references: update any existing wiki pages that should now link to the new content.
   e. Check for contradictions: if the new source contradicts existing wiki content, flag it explicitly on the relevant pages with a `> [!warning]` callout.
   f. Update `index.md` — add new pages, update summaries and source counts of modified pages.
   g. Append to `log.md`.
4. Append to `log.md` (slim format — don't list individual filenames, that info is already in `index.md`):
   ```
   ## [YYYY-MM-DD] ingest | Source Title
   - Source: [[source-filename]]
   - Impact: N summaries created, N concepts updated, N entities created
   - Key insight: one sentence summary of what this source adds to the wiki
   ```

### Query

Triggered when the human asks a question.

Steps:
1. Read `index.md` to find relevant wiki pages.
2. Read the relevant pages.
3. If wiki pages are insufficient, check `raw/` sources directly as fallback.
4. Synthesize an answer with citations to specific wiki pages: `(see [[page-name]])`.
5. If the answer is substantial and reusable, ask the human if it should be filed as a new page in `wiki/analysis/` or `wiki/comparisons/`.
6. If filed, update `index.md` and append to `log.md`:
   ```
   ## [YYYY-MM-DD] query → filed | Question summary
   - Filed as: [[actual-filename]]
   - Pages consulted: N
   ```
7. Queries that are **not filed** do NOT get logged — good answers live on as wiki pages, unfiled ones don't need a trace.

### Lint

Triggered when the human asks you to health-check the wiki.

Check for:
- **Duplicate/similar pages**: pages with highly similar titles or topics (e.g. `hooks.md` vs `hooks-claude-code.md`). **Actively merge**: keep the more complete page, fold in unique content from the other, delete the redundant file, and update all wikilinks pointing to the old file.
- **Bad filenames**: pages not following lowercase English kebab-case (containing uppercase, spaces, Chinese, parentheses, etc.). **Actively rename** and update all references.
- **Contradictions**: pages that make conflicting claims. Flag with `> [!warning]`.
- **Stale content**: claims superseded by newer sources. Mark with `> [!info] Potentially outdated`.
- **Orphan pages**: wiki pages with no inbound links from other pages.
- **Missing pages**: important concepts mentioned in wiki text but lacking their own page.
- **Missing cross-references**: pages that should link to each other but don't.
- **Missing attribution**: content paragraphs in concept/entity pages without source attribution.
- **Gaps & suggestions**: topics where knowledge is thin, with suggested search directions or material types to look for.

Write the full report to `wiki/lint-report.md` (overwrite — only keep the latest). **Actively fix** what you can (including merging duplicate pages and renaming bad filenames), and suggest actions for the rest. Historical reports are preserved via git history.

Append a slim summary to `log.md`:
```
## [YYYY-MM-DD] lint | Wiki health check
- Pages scanned: N
- Issues fixed: N, pending: N
- Report: [[lint-report]]
```

### Legacy Scan

Triggered when the human asks you to scan the legacy archive.

Steps:
1. List all files in `legacy/`.
2. For each file, read only the title (first heading) and first 10 lines.
3. Generate or update `legacy-index.md` with a table:

```markdown
| Path | Title | Summary | Tags | Quality | Wiki Relevance |
|------|-------|---------|------|---------|----------------|
| legacy/file.md | Title | One sentence | tag1, tag2 | High/Med/Low | Related to [[concept]] |
```

4. Append to `log.md`.

Do NOT read full file contents during a scan. The point is a lightweight overview, not full ingest.

## Index Format

`index.md` is organized by page type:

```markdown
# Wiki Index

## Summaries
- [[summary-name]] — One-line description (source: [[source-filename]])

## Concepts
- [[concept-name]] — One-line description (N sources)

## Entities
- [[entity-name]] — One-line description (N sources)

## Comparisons
- [[comparison-name]] — One-line description

## Analysis
- [[analysis-name]] — One-line description (from query on YYYY-MM-DD)
```

## Wikilink Rules

**All wikilinks use only the filename, never directory paths.** Obsidian locates files automatically.

- Correct: `[[attention-is-all-you-need]]`, `[[transformer-survey]]`, `[[rlhf-overview]]`
- Wrong: `[[raw/tech/attention-is-all-you-need]]`, `[[wiki/summaries/transformer]]`

This rule applies everywhere: frontmatter sources, body citations, index.md, log.md.

## Reading log.md

`log.md` is a slim operation timeline, but it grows over time. **Do not load it fully** — use tail to get recent entries:

```bash
# Last 5 operation titles
grep "^## \[" log.md | tail -5

# Last 30 lines of detail
tail -30 log.md
```

Only read further back when you need to trace a specific historical operation.

## Important Rules

1. **Never modify `raw/` or `legacy/` or `drafts/`.** Raw is immutable source of truth, legacy is frozen archive, drafts is human-owned. No moving, renaming, modifying, or deleting.
2. **Always update `index.md` and `log.md`** after any operation that changes wiki content.
3. **All wikilinks use only filenames, never paths.** This includes sources fields, body citations, index.md and log.md references.
4. **Always include frontmatter** on wiki pages.
5. **Flag contradictions explicitly** — don't silently overwrite old claims.
6. **Prefer updating existing pages over creating new ones** when the topic already has a page. Before creating, check if a synonymous or near-synonymous page already exists (e.g. `hooks` and `hooks-claude-code` are the same concept) — merge into the existing page instead.
7. **Every content section in concept/entity pages must attribute its source**, ensuring knowledge traceability. **Citations must use the actual filename of the created file** — do not fabricate or guess. Verify before writing.
8. **Ask before filing query answers** as wiki pages — the human decides what's worth keeping.
9. **One ingest at a time** unless the human explicitly asks for batch processing.
10. **Ingest: discuss first, then execute** — discuss key takeaways with the human first, then complete all file operations in one pass after consensus.
11. **Slim log principle**: ingest logs record Source + Impact numbers + Key insight (no full filename lists); only filed queries are logged; lint logs only a summary line with full report in `wiki/lint-report.md`.
